</p>
<p>
And those with extra time on their hands can also work on their writing at the annual <a target="_blank" href="https://lighthousewriters.org/" title="Lighthouse Writers Workshop">Lighthouse Writers Workshop</a> LitFest in Denver from June 5 through 20.&nbsp; There are lots of classes to take with teacher/writers such as <a target="_blank" href="http://www.freewebs.com/erikakrouse/" title="Erika Krouse">Erika Krouse</a> (who attended the University of Colorado and published stories in The New Yorker and The Atlantic), <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_steven_wingate/C39/L39/" title="Steven Wingate">Steven Wingate</a> (teaching the &#8220;Manic Short Story Intensive&#8221; with Andrea Dupree), <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_douglas_kurtz/C39/L39/" title="Doug Kurtz">Doug Kurtz</a> (teaching the seminars &#8220;Conflict, Stakes, and Motivation&#8221; and &#8220;On the Scene"), and <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_janis_hallowell/C39/L39/" title="Janis Hallowell">Janis Hallowell</a> (teaching a seminar called &#8220;Hearing Voices").&nbsp; There are also readings, parties, and &#8220;salons,&#8221; which sound pretty swank.
</p>
<p>
<a target="_blank" href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2009/may/18/cormac-mccarthy-archive-texas" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</a> noted that the Cormac McCarthy archive went on display a few weeks ago at Texas State University-San Marcos, home of the famed Southwestern Writers Collection.&nbsp; Alison Flood wrote, &#8220;McCarthy&#8217;s entire writing career, from his debut <I>The Orchard Keeper</I> to an unfinished novel <I>The Passenger</I>&#8220; is included in the 98-box archive.&nbsp; Also in those boxes: McCarthy&#8217;s &#8220;1994 play <I>The Stonemason</I>, about an African-American family in Louisville, Kentucky, and four screenplays, including <I>No Country for Old Men</I> &#8211; which McCarthy started as a screenplay in 1984 and adapted into a novel 20 years later.&#8221; (Via <a target="_blank" href="http://news.shelf-awareness.com/msgget.jsp?mid=2847390" title="Shelf Awareness">Shelf Awareness</a>.)
</p>
<p>
The trailer for the film adaptation of McCarthy&#8217;s <I>The Road</I> has <a target="_blank" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EHYZ7xDyBEw" title="recently surfaced">recently surfaced</a>, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.mediabistro.com/galleycat/adaptation/nick_cave_and_cormac_mccarthy_on_the_road_116728.asp" title="to some derision">to some derision</a>.&nbsp; <a target="_blank" href="http://booksblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2009/05/trailer-for-the-road-color-me.html" title="Michael Merschel ">Michael Merschel </a>of the Dallas Morning News described his reaction to it in this way:
</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;Ha! Somebody has made a parody of what <i>The Road</i> would look like if the adaptation of the best novel of the decade fell victim to every cliche in Hollywood! How funny!
</p>
<p>
This <i>is</i> a parody, right? &#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>
Just in time for budget-minded summer reading, the paperback editon of <a target="_blank" href="http://www.deannestillman.com" title="Deanne Stillman">Deanne Stillman</a>&#8216;s <I>Mustang: The Saga of the Wild Horse in the American West</I> is out now.&nbsp; We excerpted a portion of Stillman&#8217;s book, &#8220;Comanche: The Horse That Survived the Battle of the Little Bighorn&#8221; (<a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/comanche_the_horse_that_survived_the_battle_of_the_little_bighorn_part_1/C39/L39/" title="here">here</a> and <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/comanche_the_horse_that_survived_the_battle_of_the_little_bighorn_part_2/C39/L39/" title="here">here</a>) a few years ago, and since then the book won a California Book Award silver medal for nonfiction and was named a &#8220;Best Book of 2008&#8221; by the Los Angeles Times.
</p>
<p>
Follow me on <a target="_blank" href="http://twitter.com/jennyshank" title="Twitter">Twitter</a>, and please <script type="text/javascript">
